T1  - K-matrix-class estimators and the full-information maximum-likelihood estimator as a special case
AU  - Scharf, Werner
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 4
IS  - 1
SP  - 41
EP  - 50
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/02/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(76)90016-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407676900166
AB  - This article presents a unified treatment of simultaneous system estimation. A general class of full-information estimators is proposed, called K-matrix-class (KMC). It is shown that the K-matrix-class includes both full-information maximum-likelihood and three-stage least- squares estimators as special cases and that the k-class can be regarded as a subclass of the K-matrix-class. Conditions under which KMC estimators are consistent (similar to those of the k-class estimators) are given. Furthermore, as a full information-generalization of the double k-class estimators, the double K-matrix-class estimators (DKMC) are proposed.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Information and computation in simultaneous equations estimation
AU  - Dent, Warren
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 4
IS  - 1
SP  - 89
EP  - 95
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/02/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(76)90018-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440767690018X
AB  - The complexity and size of simultaneous equations systems necessitates great care with computations for parameter estimation. In three-stage least-squares (3SLS) large matrix inversions are required, and because of the sensitivity of many economic systems to key parameters, accuracy in estimation is important. There are many numerical techniques available which yield accurate solutions to systems of equations. We make use of Householder transformations and recursive triangulation solutions in presenting numerical algorithms for the computation of 3SLS and k-class estimates. Another numerical technique, the singular value decomposition is valuable in providing additional information in k-class estimation. The values of k for which this estimator does not exist are accurately derived, their use being demonstrated by an example.
ER  - 

